properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant amounts of snow and freezing rain expected. A low pressure system approaching the area will bring a mix of rain, snow and freezing rain. Precipitation will transition to snow or freezing rain this morning as temperatures fall to near or slightly below the freezing mark. Freezing rain may persist for several hours before completely changing over to snow later this morning. Snow will continue into Saturday night before tapering off Sunday morning. Total snowfall amounts of 15 cm are possible. In addition, strong northeasterly winds of 40 gusting to 60 km/h, combined with snow, may result in blowing snow and reduced visibility. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Spring storm on tap for Alberta… A complex weather system currently developing off the BC coast will bring a sharp change in the weather for Alberta later this weekend. Widespread and potentially heavy precipitation will be a concern for western and central portions of the province starting Sunday afternoon and continuing into Monday. Precipitation will start off as rain but will likely change to snow overnight in some locales, particularly for those higher elevations west of Edmonton and Red Deer. Strong gusty winds will also be a concern on the back side of this low, mainly in the foothills. A great deal of uncertainty still exists regarding the timing and location of the rain and snow, including the anticipated amounts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
Expires: 2020-05-03T02:45:02-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system currently over Manitoba is spreading rain through central Manitoba. Cold air will sweep into the area as this low tracks towards Ontario tonight, transitioning the rain to wet snow. The snow will continue through Saturday, leaving accumulations of 10 to 20 cm in its wake. While snow is expected throughout the Thompson region, the heavy snow will occur south of the city of Thompson. The rain will transition to snow near midnight in Norway house, and overnight in Island Lake. The snow will begin to taper off Saturday afternoon in Thompson and Saturday evening in Norway House and Island Lake. Along with the snow, there is potential for freezing rain to develop with this system, notably over the Norway House and Island Lake regions. The potential for freezing rain for these communities exists overnight and into Saturday early morning. Please refer to the public forecasts for more details. And stay alert for updated warnings. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
